    specialty: "Anaesthetics & Perioperative Medicine",
    price: 15,
    aim: "An in-depth reference for medical secretaries, consultant PAs, private practice administrators, anaesthetic secretaries and perioperative coordinators — covering anatomy, terminology, theatre pathways, investigations and private practice administration specific to anaesthetics and perioperative medicine.",
    sections: [
      { heading: "1. Introduction to Anaesthetics &amp; Perioperative Medicine", body: "<p>Anaesthetics focuses on safe care before, during and after procedures requiring anaesthesia, sedation or specialist monitoring. Perioperative medicine manages the complete surgical journey from preparation through recovery.</p><p><strong>Common pathways:</strong></p><ul><li>Surgical referral</li><li>Pre-assessment</li><li>Anaesthetic review</li><li>Risk assessment</li><li>Theatre planning</li><li>Anaesthetic procedure</li><li>Recovery</li><li>Post-operative follow-up</li></ul><p><strong>Common documents:</strong></p><ul><li>Pre-assessment notes</li><li>Anaesthetic clinic letters</li><li>Operation notes</li><li>Consent documents</li><li>Theatre lists</li><li>Pain management plans</li><li>Critical care correspondence</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "2. Anaesthetic Anatomy &amp; Clinical Terminology", body: "<ul><li><strong>Airway</strong> — Breathing passage.</li><li><strong>Trachea</strong> — Windpipe.</li><li><strong>Lungs</strong> — Breathing organs.</li><li><strong>Heart</strong> — Circulates blood.</li><li><strong>Veins</strong> — Carry blood for IV access.</li><li><strong>Nerves</strong> — Pain and sensation pathways.</li><li><strong>Spine</strong> — Site for spinal/epidural anaesthesia.</li><li><strong>Respiratory system</strong> — Breathing system.</li><li><strong>Cardiovascular system</strong> — Heart and circulation.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "3. Common Anaesthetic Conditions &amp; Considerations", body: "<p><strong>Pre-operative Concerns:</strong></p><ul><li>High blood pressure</li><li>Heart disease</li><li>Diabetes</li><li>Obesity</li><li>Sleep apnoea</li><li>Previous anaesthetic problems</li></ul><p><strong>Airway:</strong></p><ul><li>Difficult airway</li><li>Intubation concerns</li></ul><p><strong>Post-operative:</strong></p><ul><li>Nausea/vomiting</li><li>Pain control issues</li><li>Delayed recovery</li></ul><p><strong>Critical Care:</strong></p><ul><li>High dependency care</li><li>Intensive care needs</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "4. Anaesthetic Abbreviations &amp; Acronyms", body: "<ul><li><strong>GA</strong> — General anaesthetic</li><li><strong>LA</strong> — Local anaesthetic</li><li><strong>RA</strong> — Regional anaesthetic</li><li><strong>SA</strong> — Spinal anaesthetic</li><li><strong>EDA</strong> — Epidural anaesthesia</li><li><strong>IV</strong> — Intravenous</li><li><strong>ETT</strong> — Endotracheal tube</li><li><strong>LMA</strong> — Laryngeal mask airway</li><li><strong>ASA</strong> — American Society of Anaesthesiologists score</li><li><strong>PAC</strong> — Pre-assessment clinic</li><li><strong>PACU</strong> — Post anaesthetic care unit</li><li><strong>HDU</strong> — High dependency unit</li><li><strong>ICU</strong> — Intensive care unit</li><li><strong>PONV</strong> — Post-operative nausea and vomiting</li><li><strong>NBM</strong> — Nil by mouth</li><li><strong>MDT</strong> — Multidisciplinary team</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "5. Anaesthetic Investigation Dictionary", body: "<ul><li><strong>Pre-assessment</strong> — Checks patient suitability for surgery.</li><li><strong>Blood Tests</strong> — Check safety before procedures.</li><li><strong>ECG</strong> — Heart rhythm test.</li><li><strong>Chest X-ray</strong> — Assesses lungs/heart when required.</li><li><strong>Echocardiogram</strong> — Heart ultrasound.</li><li><strong>Sleep Studies</strong> — Assess sleep apnoea.</li><li><strong>Risk Assessment</strong> — Reviews anaesthetic and surgical risks.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "6. Anaesthetic Procedures Dictionary", body: "<ul><li><strong>General Anaesthetic</strong> — Patient fully asleep for procedure.</li><li><strong>Local Anaesthetic</strong> — Numbs a specific area.</li><li><strong>Regional Anaesthetic</strong> — Numbs a larger body region.</li><li><strong>Spinal Anaesthetic</strong> — Injection around spinal nerves.</li><li><strong>Epidural</strong> — Catheter technique for pain relief.</li><li><strong>Nerve Block</strong> — Targets specific nerves.</li><li><strong>Sedation</strong> — Relaxing medication during procedures.</li></ul><p><strong>Secretary checks:</strong> Procedure date, anaesthetic review needed, pre-assessment completed, medical information available, follow-up requirements.</p>" },
      { heading: "7. Anaesthetic Clinic Letter Structure", body: "<p><strong>Typical sections:</strong></p><ul><li>Reason for review</li><li>Medical history</li><li>Previous anaesthetic history</li><li>Medication review</li><li>Risk assessment</li><li>Anaesthetic plan</li><li>Post-operative considerations</li></ul><p><strong>Example phrases:</strong></p><ul><li>&ldquo;The patient was reviewed prior to surgery.&rdquo;</li><li>&ldquo;ASA grade assessed as&hellip;&rdquo;</li><li>&ldquo;Risks and benefits were discussed.&rdquo;</li><li>&ldquo;The patient is suitable to proceed.&rdquo;</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "8. Common Anaesthetic Dictation Phrases Explained", body: "<ul><li><strong>Fit for surgery</strong> — Suitable to proceed.</li><li><strong>Optimisation</strong> — Improving health before operation.</li><li><strong>High-risk patient</strong> — Additional planning required.</li><li><strong>Airway assessment</strong> — Checking breathing management.</li><li><strong>Post-operative monitoring</strong> — Observation after procedure.</li><li><strong>Enhanced recovery</strong> — Programme improving recovery after surgery.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "9. Medication Reference", body: "<ul><li><strong>Anaesthetic Agents</strong> — Medicines used during anaesthesia.</li><li><strong>Analgesics</strong> — Pain relief medication.</li><li><strong>Antiemetics</strong> — Prevent nausea.</li><li><strong>Anticoagulants</strong> — Blood thinning medication requiring planning.</li><li><strong>Sedatives</strong> — Relaxation medication.</li><li><strong>Local anaesthetics</strong> — Numbing medicines.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "10. Perioperative Pathway Terms", body: "<ul><li><strong>Pre-assessment</strong> — Before surgery checks.</li><li><strong>Consent</strong> — Agreement to treatment.</li><li><strong>WHO Checklist</strong> — Theatre safety checklist.</li><li><strong>Recovery</strong> — Immediate post-operation area.</li><li><strong>Enhanced Recovery Programme</strong> — Structured recovery pathway.</li><li><strong>Critical Care</strong> — Higher level monitoring.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "11. Theatre List Terminology", body: "<ul><li><strong>Elective</strong> — Planned surgery.</li><li><strong>Emergency</strong> — Urgent procedure.</li><li><strong>Day Case</strong> — Home same day.</li><li><strong>Inpatient</strong> — Requires hospital stay.</li><li><strong>Laterality</strong> — Correct side/site.</li><li><strong>Positioning</strong> — Patient placement for operation.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "12. Private Practice Administration", body: "<p><strong>Secretary checks:</strong></p><ul><li>Insurance authorisation</li><li>Anaesthetic fees</li><li>Theatre coordination</li><li>Consultant availability</li><li>Pre-assessment booking</li><li>Medical reports</li><li>Procedure scheduling</li><li>Follow-up tracking</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "13. Anaesthetic Dictation Cheat Sheet", body: "<p>Common words to recognise in anaesthetic dictation:</p><ul><li>Anaesthetic</li><li>Sedation</li><li>Airway</li><li>Intubation</li><li>Recovery</li><li>Epidural</li><li>Spinal</li><li>Nerve block</li><li>Pre-assessment</li><li>ASA score</li><li>Monitoring</li><li>Consent</li></ul>" },
    ],
